From bf15f026cf90f39609bc40ded4d0826ab988aa78 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Thomas Grainger <tagrain@gmail.com>
Date: Fri, 10 Jul 2026 00:00:00 +0100
Subject: [PATCH] tcp: reset the connection on a valid RST at rcv_nxt under a
 delayed ACK

PR: 296594

RFC 5961 Section 3.2 requires a RST with SEG.SEQ == RCV.NXT to reset the
connection.  tcp_do_segment() tests the exact-match reset condition against
last_ack_sent instead of rcv_nxt, and anchors the acceptance window's right
edge on last_ack_sent + rcv_wnd.  When the receiver has delayed-ACKed data
(rcv_nxt > last_ack_sent), a valid RST at rcv_nxt (the peer's SND.NXT) is left
unhandled in three ways:

  1. in-window, rcv_wnd large: the inner exact-match test accepts only
     last_ack_sent, so the RST draws a challenge ACK instead of resetting;
  2. rcv_wnd shrunk below the delayed-ACK gap: the RST at rcv_nxt falls beyond
     last_ack_sent + rcv_wnd and is silently dropped by the outer window check;
  3. rcv_wnd == 0: the zero-window arm accepts only last_ack_sent, so the RST
     is rejected there too.

In every case the connection is left ESTABLISHED (half-open): the peer that
sent the RST has already fully closed, so nothing retransmits it.  A registered
kevent/EVFILT_READ never fires, SO_ERROR == 0, and recv(..., MSG_PEEK) returns
EAGAIN, until the application gives up and closes the socket seconds later.

Accept a RST at rcv_nxt as an exact match everywhere last_ack_sent is accepted
(the in-window reset test and the zero-window arm), and anchor the window's
right edge on rcv_nxt + rcv_wnd.  This is strictly more RFC 5961-conformant (a
RST at RCV.NXT MUST reset) and does not weaken the anti-spoofing intent: an
off-path attacker must still guess rcv_nxt (or last_ack_sent) exactly;
in-window but non-exact RSTs still draw a challenge ACK.  OpenBSD (tcp_input.c
rev 1.194, 2005) and NetBSD (rev 1.296, 2009) both anchor RST validation on
rcv_nxt for exactly this delayed-ACK failure.

Each of the three sub-cases has a deterministic packetdrill regression test,
verified red/green on 15.1-RELEASE GENERIC kernels under QEMU/KVM: a kernel
with only the first two changes still fails the zero-window case (RST at
rcv_nxt, rcv_wnd == 0, delayed ACK) -- read() returns EAGAIN instead of
ECONNRESET -- and all three changes together make every case pass.

Reproducer (libc only, raw kqueue/kevent + sockets); on 15.1-RELEASE amd64 it
reproduces at ~312 / 10.3M connections in a 600s run, never on Linux:
https://github.com/graingert/asyncio-macos-loopback-rst-hang (c/repro.c)

Also reported to Apple (FB23590387) and CPython (python/cpython#153117): the
same code lineage in Darwin/xnu makes it far more frequent on macOS, and
asyncio's call_soon-deferred close surfaces it as a silent hang.
---
 sys/netinet/tcp_input.c | 8 +++++---
 1 file changed, 5 insertions(+), 3 deletions(-)

diff --git a/sys/netinet/tcp_input.c b/sys/netinet/tcp_input.c
index 35a9d76..0c0ae59 100644
--- a/sys/netinet/tcp_input.c
+++ b/sys/netinet/tcp_input.c
@@ -2129,14 +2129,16 @@ tcp_do_segment(struct tcpcb *tp, struct mbuf *m, struct tcphdr *th,
 		 *   covered by the RFC.
 		 */
 		if ((SEQ_GEQ(th->th_seq, tp->last_ack_sent) &&
-		    SEQ_LT(th->th_seq, tp->last_ack_sent + tp->rcv_wnd)) ||
-		    (tp->rcv_wnd == 0 && tp->last_ack_sent == th->th_seq)) {
+		    SEQ_LT(th->th_seq, tp->rcv_nxt + tp->rcv_wnd)) ||
+		    (tp->rcv_wnd == 0 && (tp->last_ack_sent == th->th_seq ||
+		    tp->rcv_nxt == th->th_seq))) {
 			KASSERT(tp->t_state != TCPS_SYN_SENT,
 			    ("%s: TH_RST for TCPS_SYN_SENT th %p tp %p",
 			    __func__, th, tp));
 
 			if (V_tcp_insecure_rst ||
-			    tp->last_ack_sent == th->th_seq) {
+			    tp->last_ack_sent == th->th_seq ||
+			    tp->rcv_nxt == th->th_seq) {
 				TCPSTAT_INC(tcps_drops);
 				/* Drop the connection. */
 				switch (tp->t_state) {
